tool_calls.params_as_json:
{"action": "write", "filename": "spray-foam-pro-tips", "content": "SPRAY FOAM PRO TIPS & TRICKS FOR DJ FOAM BOT

TOP APPLICATION TIPS:
1. Cut foam cans vertically instead of horizontally - easier to dispense and control
2. Use painter's tape to create clean edges and prevent overspray
3. Foam expands 3-4 times its original size - don't overfill gaps
4. Always shake cans vigorously before use to ensure proper mixing
5. Apply in thin layers rather than thick applications - prevents overheating
6. Keep cans at room temperature before application (70-80°F)
7. Use back-and-forth motion for even coverage
8. Fill larger gaps with rope caulk first, then foam for better results
9. Keep a spray can of lubricant handy - it helps clean foam tools instantly
10. Always wear nitrile gloves - foam removes skin oils and causes irritation

PROFESSIONAL TECHNIQUES:
- For ceiling applications, start from the furthest corner and work backward
- Always undercut door jams slightly so foam doesn't interfere with door operation
- Use foam-compatible lubricant on spray gun hoses to prevent buildup
- Temperature control is crucial - foam cures faster in heat, slower in cold
- For exterior applications, use UV-stable foam to prevent degradation
- When filling stud cavities, spray in a zig-zag pattern for complete coverage
- Always inspect foam after 24 hours - proper curing shows no tackiness

REPAIR & MAINTENANCE:
- Trim excess foam with serrated knife after curing (24-48 hours)
- Use mineral spirits to clean uncured foam from tools and skin
- For foam that has cured, use mechanical removal methods
- Small holes can be filled with foam backer rod and patch compound
- Always test foam compatibility with existing materials before application"}

query_params.content:
"SPRAY FOAM PRO TIPS & TRICKS FOR DJ FOAM BOT

TOP APPLICATION TIPS:
1. Cut foam cans vertically instead of horizontally - easier to dispense and control
2. Use painter's tape to create clean edges and prevent overspray
3. Foam expands 3-4 times its original size - don't overfill gaps
4. Always shake cans vigorously before use to ensure proper mixing
5. Apply in thin layers rather than thick applications - prevents overheating
6. Keep cans at room temperature before application (70-80°F)
7. Use back-and-forth motion for even coverage
8. Fill larger gaps with rope caulk first, then foam for better results
9. Keep a spray can of lubricant handy - it helps clean foam tools instantly
10. Always wear nitrile gloves - foam removes skin oils and causes irritation

PROFESSIONAL TECHNIQUES:
- For ceiling applications, start from the furthest corner and work backward
- Always undercut door jams slightly so foam doesn't interfere with door operation
- Use foam-compatible lubricant on spray gun hoses to prevent buildup
- Temperature control is crucial - foam cures faster in heat, slower in cold
- For exterior applications, use UV-stable foam to prevent degradation
- When filling stud cavities, spray in a zig-zag pattern for complete coverage

- Always test foam compatibility with existing materials before application"

tool_calls.params_as_json:
{"action": "write", "filename": "spray-foam-science-facts", "content": "SPRAY FOAM SCIENCE & TECHNICAL FACTS

FOAM CHEMISTRY:
- Spray foam is polyurethane-based, formed from isocyanates and polyols
- Two-component system: Side A (isocyanate) and Side B (polyol)
- Chemical reaction creates heat - can reach 200°F during application
- Blowing agents create foam structure - water for open-cell, chemicals for closed-cell
- Closed-cell uses HFO blowing agents (better for environment than HFC)
- Open-cell foam has 90%+ air content, closed-cell has 90%+ closed gas cells

CELL STRUCTURE DIFFERENCES:
- Open-cell: R-3.5 to R-4 per inch, breathable, vapor permeable
- Closed-cell: R-6 to R-7 per inch, impermeable, structural strength
- Open-cell density: 0.5 to 0.8 lb/ft³, Closed-cell: 1.5 to 3 lb/ft³
- Open-cell absorbs water, closed-cell is waterproof
- Closed-cell adds structural integrity to walls and roofs

THERMAL PROPERTIES:
- Foam eliminates air leakage - biggest energy loss in buildings
- Sealing air leaks can reduce energy costs by 15-30%
- Closed-cell foam achieves R-value of 7 per inch in ideal conditions
- Foam provides continuous insulation without thermal bridging
- Effective in all climates - hot, cold, humid, dry

CURING PROCESS:
- Initial set: 10-15 minutes (tack-free)
- Full cure: 24-48 hours (maximum strength)
- Expands 3-4 times original size during application
- Temperature affects cure time - faster in heat, slower in cold
- Proper ventilation required during application for chemical safety"}

tool_calls.params_as_json:
{"action": "write", "filename": "spray-foam-safety-info", "content": "SPRAY FOAM SAFETY & HEALTH PROTOCOLS

PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT (PPE):
- Respiratory protection: NIOSH-approved respirator with organic vapor cartridges
- Chemical-resistant gloves: Nitrile or neoprene (not latex)
- Protective clothing: Coveralls, chemical-resistant apron, boot covers
- Eye protection: Chemical safety goggles or full-face shield
- Skin protection: Barrier cream exposed skin areas
- Hearing protection: When using application equipment

HAZARDOUS EXPOSURES:
- Inhalation: Isocyanates can cause respiratory sensitization
- Skin contact: Can cause chemical burns, dermatitis, sensitization
- Eye contact: Severe irritation, potential corneal damage
- Chemical reactions: Heat generation during application (200°F)
- Uncured foam: Contains unreacted isocyanates and other chemicals
- Off-gassing: Can occur during application and curing process

WORKSITE SAFETY:
- Ventilation: Minimum 10 air changes per hour during application
- Restrict access: Only trained personnel should be present
- Emergency equipment: Eye wash station, safety shower readily available
- Spill containment: Absorbent materials for chemical spills
- Fire safety: No open flames, sparks near application areas
- Temperature control: Maintain optimal working conditions

FIRST AID PROCEDURES:
- Skin contact: Wash immediately with soap and water for 15+ minutes
- Eye contact: Flush with water for 15+ minutes, seek medical attention
- Inhalation: Move to fresh air, seek medical help if breathing difficulties
- Swallowing: Do NOT induce vomiting, seek immediate medical help
- Clothing contamination: Remove contaminated clothing immediately

SAFETY TRAINING REQUIREMENTS:
- OSHA Hazard Communication Standard training
- Product-specific safety data sheet (SDS) review
- Emergency procedures and first aid certification
- Proper PPE selection and usage training
- Chemical handling and storage procedures"}

tool_calls.params_as_json:
{"action": "write", "filename": "spray-foam-environmental-impact", "content": "SPRAY FOAM ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT & SUSTAINABILITY

CARBON FOOTPRINT:
- Spray foam reduces greenhouse gas emissions through energy savings
- Closed-cell foam with HFO blowing agents has 75% lower GWP than HFC
- Energy savings: 15-30% reduction in heating/cooling costs
- Lifecycle carbon footprint: Lower due to durability (50+ year lifespan)
- Embodied carbon: Higher than some materials, but operational savings offset

BLOWING AGENTS:
- HFCs (hydrofluorocarbons): High global warming potential, being phased out
- HFOs (hydrofluoroolefins): Low GWP, next-generation blowing agents
- Water-based: Used in open-cell foam, minimal environmental impact
- Natural options: Some emerging bio-based alternatives
- 2025 nationwide ban on HFC closed-cell spray foam systems

SUSTAINABILITY BENEFITS:
- Energy efficiency: Reduces building energy consumption significantly
- Air sealing: Eliminates thermal bridging and air infiltration
- Durability: 50+ year lifespan reduces replacement waste
- Reduced material use: High R-value means thinner installations
- Recyclability: Some companies now offer foam recycling programs

ENVIRONMENTAL CONCERNS:
- VOC emissions: During application and curing process
- Chemical waste: Uncured foam and application residue
- Manufacturing impact: Petrochemical-based materials
- Disposal challenges: Cured foam not easily recyclable
- Resource extraction: Petroleum-based raw materials

EMERGING SOLUTIONS:
- Bio-based polyols: Reducing petroleum dependency
- Low-VOC formulations: Minimizing emissions
- Recycling programs: For waste foam materials
- Carbon footprint labeling: Product sustainability certifications
- Green building certifications: LEED, Energy Star, etc. recognition
- Circular economy initiatives: Foam reuse and recycling programs"}
